  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Temperature is the most direct control over output variance in language models. Setting it correctly is the first step toward deterministic or near-deterministic outputs. But temperature alone does not guarantee reproducibility \u2014 several additional factors contribute to non-determinism even at temperature 0, and understanding them is essential for building reliable applications."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Temperature and determinism spectrum",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How Temperature Controls Variance"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At each generation step, the model produces a probability distribution over its entire vocabulary. Temperature scales the logits (the raw scores) before the softmax that converts them to probabilities:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With temperature "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "T"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each logit "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "z_i"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is divided by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "T"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " before softmax. When "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "T < 1"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", high-probability tokens become relatively more likely and the distribution sharpens. When "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "T > 1"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", the distribution flattens and low-probability tokens become more competitive."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef softmax_with_temperature(logits: np.ndarray, temperature: float) -> np.ndarray:\n    if temperature == 0:\n        # Greedy: always pick argmax\n        probs = np.zeros_like(logits)\n        probs[np.argmax(logits)] = 1.0\n        return probs\n    scaled = logits / temperature\n    exp = np.exp(scaled - scaled.max())  # numerical stability\n    return exp / exp.sum()\n\n# Example: two competing tokens with logits [2.0, 1.8]\nlogits = np.array([2.0, 1.8])\nfor t in [0.0, 0.3, 0.7, 1.0]:\n    probs = softmax_with_temperature(logits, t)\n    print(f\"T={t}: token_A={probs[0]:.3f}, token_B={probs[1]:.3f}\")\n# T=0.0: token_A=1.000, token_B=0.000   (greedy)\n# T=0.3: token_A=0.731, token_B=0.269\n# T=0.7: token_A=0.577, token_B=0.423\n# T=1.0: token_A=0.550, token_B=0.450   (near-uniform for close logits)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setting Temperature via the API"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\n# Temperature 0: maximum consistency, greedy decoding\ndef classify_deterministic(text: str) -> str:\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n        max_tokens=128,\n        temperature=0,  # greedy\n        system=\"Classify the sentiment. Reply with one word: Positive, Neutral, or Negative.\",\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": text}]\n    )\n    return resp.content[0].text.strip()\n\n# Temperature 0.7: default \u2014 balanced creativity and consistency\ndef explain_concept(concept: str) -> str:\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n        max_tokens=512,\n        temperature=0.7,\n        system=\"Explain the concept in plain language for a non-expert audience.\",\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": concept}]\n    )\n    return resp.content[0].text\n\n# Temperature 1.0: high diversity for creative tasks\ndef brainstorm_ideas(topic: str, n: int = 5) -> list[str]:\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n        max_tokens=256,\n        temperature=1.0,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": f\"Generate {n} creative ideas for: {topic}\"}]\n    )\n    return resp.content[0].text.strip().split(\"\\n\")[:n]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Temperature 0 Is Not Fully Deterministic"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Despite setting temperature to 0, the Anthropic API does not guarantee bit-for-bit identical outputs across all calls. Three sources of non-determinism persist:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Floating-point non-determinism:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " GPU matrix multiplications are parallelised with non-associative floating-point operations. Different thread orderings on different hardware produce logit values that differ in the last few bits \u2014 enough to change which token is the argmax."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Infrastructure routing:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The API may route your request to different servers, GPUs, or model replicas. Each may apply different kernel fusion or quantization strategies, producing slightly different logits."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Token tie-breaking:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " When two tokens have identical (or nearly identical) probabilities after floating-point operations, the tie-breaking rule is implementation-defined. This is rare but produces occasional unexpected outputs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, temperature 0 produces the same output on the overwhelming majority of calls for a given prompt. The non-determinism is infrequent and typically inconsequential for most applications. For applications that require guaranteed reproducibility (regulatory, audit, unit tests), cache the output rather than re-calling the API."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring Empirical Determinism"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rather than assuming temperature 0 is deterministic, measure it for your specific prompt and use case. Run N calls and count identical outputs:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import Counter\n\ndef measure_determinism(\n    prompt: str,\n    system: str = \"\",\n    temperature: float = 0.0,\n    n_runs: int = 20,\n    model: str = \"claude-opus-4-8\"\n) -> dict:\n    outputs = []\n    for _ in range(n_runs):\n        kwargs = {\n            \"model\": model,\n            \"max_tokens\": 256,\n            \"temperature\": temperature,\n            \"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}]\n        }\n        if system:\n            kwargs[\"system\"] = system\n        resp = client.messages.create(**kwargs)\n        outputs.append(resp.content[0].text.strip())\n\n    counts = Counter(outputs)\n    most_common, most_common_count = counts.most_common(1)[0]\n    return {\n        \"n_runs\": n_runs,\n        \"n_unique\": len(counts),\n        \"mode_frequency\": most_common_count / n_runs,\n        \"is_deterministic\": len(counts) == 1,\n        \"mode_output\": most_common,\n        \"distribution\": dict(counts)\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Caching for True Reproducibility"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If your application requires guaranteed identical outputs (e.g., for audit trails, regression tests, or cost control), cache the response rather than relying on temperature 0 to reproduce it. A simple content-addressed cache keyed on (model, system, messages, temperature) provides deterministic behavior with zero inference cost on cache hits:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import hashlib, json\nfrom functools import lru_cache\n\nclass DeterministicCache:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._store: dict[str, str] = {}\n\n    def _key(self, model: str, system: str, messages: list, temperature: float) -> str:\n        payload = json.dumps(\n            {\"model\": model, \"system\": system, \"messages\": messages, \"temp\": temperature},\n            sort_keys=True\n        )\n        return hashlib.sha256(payload.encode()).hexdigest()\n\n    def get_or_call(\n        self,\n        model: str,\n        system: str,\n        messages: list,\n        temperature: float = 0.0,\n        max_tokens: int = 512\n    ) -> str:\n        key = self._key(model, system, messages, temperature)\n        if key not in self._store:\n            resp = client.messages.create(\n                model=model, max_tokens=max_tokens,\n                temperature=temperature, system=system,\n                messages=messages\n            )\n            self._store[key] = resp.content[0].text\n        return self._store[key]\n\ncache = DeterministicCache()\n# First call: hits API. Subsequent calls with same args: returns cached value.\nresult = cache.get_or_call(\n    model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n    system=\"Classify sentiment.\",\n    messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Great product!\"}],\n    temperature=0.0\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt Sensitivity and Determinism"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even at temperature 0, the output is highly sensitive to the exact prompt text. Adding or removing a trailing space, changing word order, or modifying capitalization can flip the mode output. This is not a bug \u2014 it reflects the model's sensitivity to its conditioning context."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Two implications for production systems:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Version-control your prompts. A prompt edit that looks cosmetic may change outputs. Treat prompt changes with the same discipline as code changes \u2014 test against a held-out eval set before deploying."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cache keys must include the full prompt text. If your cache key only includes the user query and not the system prompt, a system prompt change will silently return stale cached outputs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Top-p (Nucleus Sampling) and Its Interaction with Temperature"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Anthropic API also exposes a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "top_p"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter (nucleus sampling). When set, only the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "top_p"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are considered at each step. Anthropic recommends altering either temperature or top_p, not both:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use temperature to control overall diversity. This is the primary knob."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use top_p only if you need to hard-cap token diversity to a nucleus regardless of the full distribution shape. Leave it at its default (1.0) for most tasks."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Combining both (temperature < 1 AND top_p < 1) produces complex interactions that are hard to reason about and tune."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Seed-Based Reproducibility"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Some APIs and local inference frameworks support a random seed parameter that initialises the sampling RNG. When both temperature and seed are fixed, and the model runs on identical hardware, outputs are typically bit-identical. The Anthropic API does not currently expose a seed parameter \u2014 use caching as the reliable reproducibility mechanism instead."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For local inference (e.g., running open-weight models via vLLM or llama.cpp), seed control is available and sufficient for reproducibility on a single GPU with identical batch sizes. Cross-GPU and multi-GPU setups reintroduce floating-point non-determinism even with fixed seeds."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Example: seed control with a local vLLM server\n# (not available on Anthropic API \u2014 shown for contrast)\nfrom openai import OpenAI  # vLLM serves an OpenAI-compatible endpoint\n\nlocal_client = OpenAI(base_url=\"http://localhost:8000/v1\", api_key=\"none\")\n\ndef local_deterministic_call(prompt: str, seed: int = 42) -> str:\n    resp = local_client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=\"meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct\",\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}],\n        temperature=0.0,\n        seed=seed  # available in vLLM / OpenAI API\n    )\n    return resp.choices[0].message.content\n\n# For Anthropic API: use response caching instead\n# seed is not available; temperature=0 gives high but not guaranteed consistency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Eval Implications: Testing Across Temperature Settings"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Your eval suite should test both the happy-path content and format stability across multiple temperature settings and multiple runs. A prompt that produces correct outputs at T=0 may produce incorrect outputs at T=0.7 if the model is uncertain about the answer \u2014 that variance reveals model confidence, which is diagnostic information."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def temperature_sensitivity_report(\n    cases: list[dict],  # [{\"input\": ..., \"expected\": ...}]\n    answer_fn,          # fn(input, temperature) -> str\n    temperatures: list[float] = [0.0, 0.3, 0.7, 1.0],\n    n_per_setting: int = 5\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Measure accuracy across temperature settings to find the optimal T.\"\"\"\n    results = {}\n    for t in temperatures:\n        scores = []\n        for case in cases:\n            for _ in range(n_per_setting):\n                output = answer_fn(case[\"input\"], t)\n                scores.append(case[\"expected\"].lower() in output.lower())\n        results[t] = {\n            \"accuracy\": sum(scores) / len(scores),\n            \"n\": len(scores)\n        }\n    return results\n\n# Pattern: choose the highest temperature that maintains accuracy above threshold\ndef optimal_temperature(\n    report: dict,\n    accuracy_threshold: float = 0.95\n) -> float:\n    eligible = [\n        t for t, r in report.items()\n        if r[\"accuracy\"] >= accuracy_threshold\n    ]\n    return max(eligible) if eligible else min(report.keys())"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Running a temperature sensitivity report during prompt development tells you how fragile your prompt is. A prompt that achieves 95% accuracy at T=0 but drops to 70% at T=0.5 is too sensitive to stochastic variance \u2014 it will behave inconsistently even in production at T=0 due to the residual non-determinism described earlier. Robust prompts maintain accuracy across a range of temperatures."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Combining Temperature with Other Consistency Techniques"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Temperature is one layer in the consistency stack. The most reliable systems combine all layers:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
